Gome, Great Wall, Lenovo, Minmetals: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-27T01:02:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-27/gome-great-wall-lenovo-minmetals-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose 0.7 percent to 22,900.79. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, gained 0.5 percent to 12,752.08.  Hong Kong Banks: The Hong Kong Monetary Authority asked
local banks to conduct stress tests after a surge in loans
outpaced deposit growth, raising concerns over liquidity.  The de facto central bank asked lenders to assume half of
the HK$1.38 trillion ($177 billion) of customer deposits in
local and foreign currencies added since late 2008 will flow out
in six to 12 months, it said in an e-mailed reply to written
questions from Bloomberg News yesterday.  Hang Seng Bank Ltd. (11)  (11 HK), the Hong Kong-based lender
backed by HSBC Holdings Plc (5 HK), rose 0.2 percent to
HK$123.70. BOC Hong Kong (Holdings) Ltd. (2388 HK), the Hong
Kong unit of China’s third-largest lender by market value,
declined 0.4 percent to HK$23.50.  China Banks: China’s six largest banks must submit capital
adequacy ratio calculations by June 3 under a new timetable from
the China Banking Regulatory Commission,  China Daily  reported,
citing the regulator.  China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (939 HK), the nation’s No. 2
lender by market value, increased 0.4 percent to HK$7.15.
 Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (1398)  Ltd. (1398 HK), China’s
biggest bank by market value rose 0.7 percent to HK$6.23.  Gome Electrical Appliances Holding Ltd. (493 HK): China’s
second-largest electronics retailer said first-quarter profit
surged 66 percent from a year earlier to 552 million yuan ($85
million). The stock fell 0.7 percent to HK$2.81.  Great Wall Motor Co. (2333 HK): China’s largest maker of
 pickup trucks  agreed to buy the outstanding 47 percent stake in
Baoding Great Wall Huabei Automobile Co. from the liquidators of
its bankrupt partner for 173.2 million yuan. Great Wall
decreased 2.1 percent to HK$12.02.  Lenovo Group Ltd. (992)  (992 HK): China’s biggest maker of
personal computers said fourth-quarter profit tripled to $42
million, exceeding the $38.4 million average estimate from six
analysts estimates compiled by Bloomberg. The stock gained 0.7
percent to HK$4.33.  Minmetals Resources Ltd. (1208)  (1208 HK): The former suitor for
Equinox Minerals Ltd. (EQN CN), said it will accept the offer of
rival bidder Barrick Gold Corp. (ABX CN) for its stake in the
copper miner, booking a net gain of about $150.4 million.
Minmetals gained 4 percent to HK$5.50.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK): China’s largest oil company said
parent China National Petroleum Corp. bought 31.1 million yuan-
denominated shares, equivalent to a 0.017 percent stake, in the
company on May 25. PetroChina advanced 1.5 percent to HK$10.54.  Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd. (16)  (16 HK): The world’s biggest
developer by market value is seeking HK$45,000 ($5,782) per
square foot for an apartment, the Standard reported, citing
Kenneth Wu, a real estate agent at Ricacorp Properties Ltd. The
stock dropped 0.5 percent to HK$117.60.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Tokyo at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story: Nick Gentle at
   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 